To change the color of the jokes to red using CSS, you can add a style directly to the `<p>` tag that displays the joke, or you can define a class in a `<style>` block (or an external stylesheet) and apply that class to the joke paragraph. Here's how you can do it by adding a class:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Joke Generator</title>
    <style>
        /* CSS to change the joke color to red */
        .joke-text {
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Random Joke Generator</h1>
    <button onclick="showRandomJoke()">Tell me a joke</button>
    <p id="joke" class="joke-text"></p> <!-- Apply the class here -->

    <script>
        // Array of jokes
        const jokes = [
            "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything.",
            "I told my wife she should embrace her mistakes. She gave me a hug.",
            "Why do we tell actors to 'break a leg'? Because every play has a cast.",
            "Parallel lines have so much in common. It’s a shame they’ll never meet."
        ];

        function showRandomJoke() {
            // Get a random index
            const index = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
            // Select the joke paragraph
            const jokeElement = document.getElementById("joke");
            // Set the text of the joke paragraph to a random joke
            jokeElement.innerText = jokes[index];
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, a CSS class named `.joke-text` is defined within a `<style>` block in the `<head>` section of the HTML document. This class sets the `color` property to `red`. The class is then applied to the `<p>` tag with the id `joke` by adding `class="joke-text"` to it. This way, any text that appears within this paragraph will be displayed in red, including the jokes when they are shown.

To find the top-2 most occurring elements in an array, you can adapt a similar approach to the Boyer-Moore Voting Algorithm, but this time, you need to keep track of two potential candidates and their counts. The idea is to essentially run a "tournament" among elements, where candidates are selected based on their frequencies, and then verify their counts at the end to ensure they are indeed the top-2 most occurring elements.

Here's how you can implement this in Python:

```python
def findTop2MostOccurring(nums):
    # Initialize two candidates and their counts
    candidate1, candidate2, count1, count2 = None, None, 0, 0

    # Step 1: Find candidates for the top-2 most occurring elements
    for num in nums:
        if candidate1 == num:
            count1 += 1
        elif candidate2 == num:
            count2 += 1
        elif count1 == 0:
            candidate1, count1 = num, 1
        elif count2 == 0:
            candidate2, count2 = num, 1
        else:
            count1, count2 = count1 - 1, count2 - 1

    # Step 2: Verify the candidates by counting their occurrences
    count1, count2 = 0, 0
    for num in nums:
        if num == candidate1:
            count1 += 1
        elif num == candidate2:
            count2 += 1

    # Determine if we have found the top-2 most occurring elements
    result = []
    if count1 > len(nums) // 3:
        result.append(candidate1)
    if count2 > len(nums) // 3:
        result.append(candidate2)

    return result

# Example usage
nums = [1, 1, 1, 2, 3, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 3]
print(findTop2MostOccurring(nums))
```

This function works by first finding two candidates that could potentially be the top-2 most occurring elements. It does this by iterating through the array and adjusting the counts and candidates based on the current element. After identifying potential candidates, it verifies them by counting their occurrences in a second pass through the array.

Note that this function checks if the candidates occur more than ⌊n/3⌋ times to ensure that it's possible to have two elements that are "most occurring" under this definition. If you're strictly looking for the top-2 regardless of their actual counts, you might need to adjust this threshold based on your specific requirements.

